post_text: Shout out to all of our dedicated TC fans, staff, students, parents, and families. We may be small, but we are strong. We may not always get the win but we keep thriving. One of the best parts of our school is our pride. We get back up if we fall down. We stand united when times are tough. We support one another which is evident by our school spirit and our community support. We are a Trojan family. Always. I am proud to be part of a close knit community and school. #tcpride üíõüñ§

post_text:
Parents/Senior Night -(Football and Cheer)

Dear Parents,

Friday, September 4, is Parent/Senior Night for football and cheer. We will honor our senior athletes and recognize parents before the football game at 6:45 P.M.. Parents of cheerleaders and players will get into the game for free as usual, however, they will not be allowed to come down on the field. We ask parents to stand when their names are called and their son or daughter will go to the sideline and face the crowd.

Senior parents - Please meet your child at the gap between the fence and the bleachers on the South end. Seniors will meet their parents on the track and social distance from the rest of the group.

Contact the school if you have any questions or concerns. Masks are highly encouraged at the game. Thank you for your support of Trojan Athletics.

Dear TC Students and Families,

This is a reminder for the PK-12 Open House which is being held tomorrow, August 19th. PK-6th is requested to come between 5:00 p.m.-6:00 p.m. to bring their supplies to their room and meet their teacher. 7th-12th grade is requested to come between 6:00 p.m.-7:00 p.m. I would plan to take your child‚Äôs school picture at this time in front of their lockers and clsssrooms. Masks are highly welcomed and each classroom has a 15 person capacity for Open House. The free meal will be provided by the TC School Board and will be outside to practice social distancing. Please bring back any school textbooks and any school-issued athletic uniforms you may have. Please note: The first day of school is August 24th. Preschool starts on August 31st. Please remember there are no visitors and families in the building at this time. I greatly appreciate your support. We look forward to seeing everyone. Take care, ~Ms. Berg #tcpride

post_text:
TC Baseball finishes 2-13

The Trojan's season came to an end Saturday against the SICL champs from HLV. This was a great group of kids who kept getting better throughout the season. The team raised its batting average from at .247 in 2019 to a .322 in 2020. The administration wishes seniors Tegon Fogle and Brayden Monroe the best in their future endeavors. Thank you parents and fans for your support during the season. Although the record doesn't show it, this was a much improved, competitive team.

Proud to be a Trojan!
Coach Edmundson

Dear TC: Several of you have participated in the Technology Access Survey and we thank you. As a reminder, the state‚Äôs Technology Access Survey will close at 11:59 p.m. on Wednesday, June 24. We strongly encourage you to share the following link with each household in your district/nonpublic school and emphasize why it is important to respond.

Survey link: http://bit.ly/iowatechsurvey

The survey should take no longer than five minutes to complete and will help the state to better understand the specific technology needs of PK-12 and postsecondary learners. The information will help us determine how to best use the Governor‚Äôs Emergency Education Relief (GEER), which focuses on providing and expanding broadband access and improving access to technology in other ways.

Stay safe. Thank you! ~Ms. Berg

post_text: Good Morning! This is a neat do-it-yourself activity. Pretty neat!
shared_text:
7 Days of Play
May 24 at 7:54 AM ¬∑

üéæ POOL NOODLE TENNIS RACKETS // Are your pool noodles from last summer looking a little shabby? üôã‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è Turn them into tennis rackets instead of tossing them in the trash! Because oh my gosh guys ü§ó ‚Äî look how cool they turned out! üè∏ This might be one of my favorite pool noodle hacks ever. üôå All you need is a pool noodle, recycled plastic netting (like the ones you get with bulk fruit buys!) ‚ôªÔ∏è, and tape. Read on below üëá for the instructions. Any questions at all? Drop them in the comment section below!
-
INSTRUCTIONS
(1) Slice off a 6 inch half from the ends of a pool noodle (I repeat, just a half ‚Äî don‚Äôt cut the whole bottom!), so that when you bring the ends together it makes a racket handle.
(2) Tape the handle together (we used gorilla tape).
(3) Slip the plastic netting over the loop. We used the netting from bulk bags of avocados.
(4) Secure the plastic netting with a final piece of tape.

Because oh my gosh guys ü§ó ‚Äî look how cool they turned out! üè∏ This might be one of my favorite pool noodle hacks ever. üôå All you need is a pool noodle, recycled plastic netting (like the ones you get with bulk fruit buys!) ‚ôªÔ∏è, and tape. Dear Seniors:

Tomorrow is the big day! Reminder: please show up in front of the HS for pictures at 11:00 a.m. promptly. You will have your pictures one by one inside the building on the stage. I have extra order forms if you need them. Shelly will have your medals and cords for you to wear as well as the flowers. After pictures are completed you will need to be in the same vehicle as your parents/guardians to enter the field. Commencement will begin at 1:00 p.m. The parade will follow the ceremony and be down Main Street in What Cheer. We will line up in front of the HS to start the parade and you'll follow me in the school suburban. Graduation will be live-streamed on the TC Facebook page. If the weather does not permit, Mr. Straight will make the decision to postpone tomorrow morning and we will announce this at 10:00 a.m. We will then schedule graduation to Saturday, May 23rd at 1:00 p.m. I'm excited to see you tomorrow. Thank you! ~Ms. Berg
text:
Dear Seniors:

Tomorrow is the big day! Reminder: please show up in front of the HS for pictures at 11:00 a.m. promptly. You will have your pictures one by one inside the building on the stage. I have extra order forms if you need them. Shelly will have your medals and cords for you to wear as well as the flowers. After pictures are completed you will need to be in the same vehicle as your parents/guardians to enter the field. Commencement will begin at 1:00 p.m. The parade will follow the ceremony and be down Main Street in What Cheer. We will line up in front of the HS to start the parade and you'll follow me in the school suburban. Graduation will be live-streamed on the TC Facebook page. If the weather does not permit, Mr. Straight will make the decision to postpone tomorrow morning and we will announce this at 10:00 a.m. We will then schedule graduation to Saturday, May 23rd at 1:00 p.m. I'm excited to see you tomorrow. Thank you! ~Ms. Berg

post_text:
Dear Tri-County Graduates and families,

I hope you are all well. In the case of inclement weather, the TC Administration will make the decision to hold the graduation ceremony on Saturday, May 16th at 10:00 a.m. We will send out a message alert and post on social media. If the weather does not permit the rain date will be on Saturday, May 23rd at 1:00 p.m. on the football field. We hope the weather is clear for our ceremony to honor our graduates. Thank you, ~TC Admin.

Dear Tri-County Families,

This is a gentle reminder about the Senior Parade being held on Friday, April 17th. The Seniors and staff participating will be meeting at the TC High School parking lot at 12:00 p.m. The parade will start in What Cheer at 1:00 p.m. and roughly be back in Keswick at 1:30 p.m. I have included the parade routes for What Cheer and Keswick in this email. We invite everyone to be outside their houses (hopefully with no snow) and show support to our graduating Seniors. We want to make sure you are continuing to practice social distancing and staying safe. Take care and I hope to see you on Friday! ~Ms. Berg

post_text:
Hrasky's Creative Writing Club!

I'm starting a creative writing club for any students looking for a creative outlet! I'll be posting prompts on the GoogleClassroom site I just set up. Prompts will be everything from writing stories to expressing your opinion! I'm going to try to keep it fun! I sent out invitations to join the group via email to all students 9-12. Let me know if there are any students in other grades who would like to join. Should be a great way to get kid's brains working and keep their writing skills sharp! And who knows, maybe I'll use this to help me write the school play for next Fall!

Vince Hrasky

Something I think you might enjoy. Similar style to how I make one. I do a pinch bow vs the one she made. I will be sending you photos throughout the week via text on the phone. Let me know if you would rather receive it by email. The material I share with you is things we would have covered had we been in school.

Hopefully we are back in school by May 1. Until then- stay safe. This virus is serious and it will get to our area.

The flower for this week is a daffodil. You might recognize the photo location. In front of my machine shed.
The daffodil is a bulb plant that can survive our cold winters...meaning you do not need to dig them up in the fall. You plant them in fall and they come up each year at or around this time. The idea of a perennial flower bed is to have blooms starting in early spring through late fall. COMING SOON- iris blooms. ( I bet you can't wait!!)

Mr.Streigel

post_text:
Severe Weather Week-- Tornadoes

This week is Severe Weather Awareness Week. TC wants to remind you to discuss safety plans with your children in the event that a severe weather warning is issued. Have a plan in place for the family. Know where to go when warnings and watches are issued.

WATCH: BE PREPARED!
WARNING: TAKE ACTION!

Also since everyone is spending more time at home, this is a good time to remember to check your fire alarms. Many fatalities happen when alarms are not maintained. Take time to go over emergency action plans with children:

How to evacuate?
Where to go and set up a meeting spot away from the hazard?
DO NOT RETURN INTO BURNING HOUSE
Run a drill with your kids using the fire alarm.
(It is disturbing to find out how many kids do not wake up to an alarm)

Sometimes the little thing are overlooked. Enjoy the day and be safe TC community.

Feel free to share with others.

This is just a reminder, for the middle school reading classes, that I encourage you to keep writing during the school closure. Here is a few topics that you can consider writing about:

* You can keep a journal about your experiences with the quarantine.

* You can write about a dream vacation you would like to go on in the future.

* You can write an interesting story about why the weather keeps changing so frequently (fact or fiction).

*You are also more than welcome to write about something else that interests you.

When you are finished with your writing please remember to email it to me. I look forward to reading what you have written. Of course, this is all optional and will not be graded.

Take care,
Mrs. Ryan

Please stay safe, be smart, and I hope to see you all very soon!

-Mr. Springer
